Silole compounds are attractive materials for silole-based π-electronic compounds [


  26–28


]. In particular, their metal complexes are key intermediates or precursors in the transition metal-catalyzed synthesis of silole-based π-electronic compounds or π-conjugated polymers. In this context, we attempted oxidative addition reactions of dihalosilole derivatives to the Pd(0) compound [Pd(styrene)(PMe

 3

)

 2

]. These reactions afforded mono- or dinuclear Pd(II) compounds bearing a silole moiety, depending on the molar ratio (

 Scheme 3

). The dimethyl silole Pd(II) compound is unstable in halogenated organic solvents. To the best of our knowledge, this represents the first time that mono- or dinuclear silole-bridged Pd(II) complexes have been reported.

